61","1382":"1382","1348":"1348","1458":"1458","1359":"1359","1400":"1400","1345":"1345","1366":"1366","1355":"1355","1322":"1322","1365":"1365","1320":"1320","1441":"1441","about 1345":"about 1345","about 1368":"about 1368","Netherfield, Sussex, England":"Netherfield, Sussex, England","Rotherfield, Sussex, England":"Rotherfield, Sussex, England","Winchelsea, Sussex, , England":"Winchelsea, Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Herbert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German, English, and French: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. In Britain, this Old French name, introduced by the Normans, reinforced the less common Old English cognate <i>Herebeorht</i>. The surname was taken to Ireland after the Anglo-Norman invasion and in the 16th century.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the German personal name (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Harbison","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): patronymic from the Older Scots and Middle English personal name   Herbert   (the change from <i>-er-</i> to <i>-ar-</i> was a common one in Old French and Middle English). An intrusive <i>n</i> later gave   Harbinson  ."]},{"name":"Hebard","meanings":["English (Surrey):","variant of   Herbert  , with assimilation of the first <i>r</i>. Compare   Hebb  .","variant of   Hibbert  ."]},{"name":"Harbert","meanings":["German and English: variant of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herbers","meanings":["German and Dutch: patronymic from   Herbert  . It is found mainly in Lower Saxony and across the Dutch border."]},{"name":"Dickherber","meanings":["Probably a nickname for a fat person by the name of   Herbert  , of which <i>Herber</i> is a short form, or, more likely, in the north from <b>Die(c)kherber</b>, a topographic and distinguishing name for a <i>Herber</i> living by the dike, see   Dicke   2. Compare   Dickmeyer  ."]},{"name":"Hebert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Emile, Normand, Jacques, Marcel, Pierre, Lucien, Michel, Gaston, Alcide, Camille.","French (<b>Hébert</b>): assimilated form of   Herbert  . Compare   Abair  ,   Abar  ,   Abare  ,   Abear  ,   Aber  ,   Eber  , and   Ebert  .","German: variant of   Heber   1."]},{"name":"Herber","meanings":["German and Dutch: variant of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herbertson","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): patronymic from the Older Scots and Middle English personal name   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Hebb","meanings":["English (East Yorkshire and northeast Midlands): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hebb</i>, <i>Ebb</i>, pet forms of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herb","meanings":["South German: nickname for a harsh or rough person, from Middle High German <i>herb</i> ‘tart, harsh’.","German: from the personal name <i>Herpo</i>, a pet form of   Herbert  ."]}]},{"name":"Finch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>finch</i>, <i>fink</i> ‘finch’ (Old English <i>finc</i>), for a small, lively, cheerful person.","Americanized form (translation into English) of German, Jewish (Ashkenazic), Czech, Slovenian, and Croatian   Fink   ‘finch’, or of some of the corresponding Slavic surnames, e.g. Czech (Moravian) <b>Pěnka</b> (see   Penka  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Fink","meanings":["German, Jewish (Ashkenazic), Danish, and English: nickname for a lively and cheerful person, or, in the case of the Jewish name, an artificial name, from Middle High German <i>vinke</i>, Middle English and Yiddish <i>fink</i> ‘finch’ (see   Finch   and   Vink  ). The surname of German origin is also found in some central European countries, for example in Czechia, Slovenia, and Croatia, often as a translation into German of corresponding Slavic nicknames or surnames. In part, this is a Gottscheerish (i.e. Gottschee German) surname, originating from the Kočevsko region in Lower Carniola, Slovenia (see   Kocevar  )."]}]},{"name":"Vincent","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vincens</i> ‘conquering’ (genitive <i>Vincentis</i>). This name was borne by various early saints particularly associated with France, most notably the 5th-century  St Vincent of Lérins ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Vincent Herbert Finch III was born about 1345, in Netherfield, Sussex, England, his father, Henry Herbert Finch, was 27 and his mother, Parnell Allard, was 25. He married Joan Passenden about 1368. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1384, in Rotherfield, Sussex, England, at the age of 40."},"et":{"about 1345–1384":"umbes 1345–1384","1345–1384":"1345–1384","1359–1458":"1359–1458","1361–Female":"1361–Surnud","1361–Male":"1361–Surnud","1363–Female":"1363–Surnud","1365–Male":"1365–Surnud","1348–1400":"1348–1400","1366–1441":"1366–1441","1383–Male":"1383–Surnud","1320–1385":"1320–1385","1322–1400":"1322–1400","1385":"1385","1363":"1363","1384":"1384","1383":"1383","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1348":"1348","1458":"1458","1359":"1359","1400":"1400","1345":"1345","1366":"1366","1355":"1355","1322":"1322","1365":"1365","1320":"1320","1441":"1441","about 1345":"umbes 1345","about 1368":"umbes 1368","Netherfield, Sussex, England":"Netherfield, Sussex, England","Rotherfield, Sussex, England":"Rotherfield, Susse